EPISTLE IV.

, Tms Epistle is addressed to Albius Tibullus, the poet, to whom also C. i. 33 is written. The letter only professes to be one to inquire after Tibul- lus3 but occasion is taken to commend his fortunes and himself, and to bid him live every day as isit were the last. Horace writes to his friend (proba- bly from Rome) at his place near Pedum, a town of Latium, not far from Praeneste. There Tibullus had ‚a good estate, inherited from his father, which, before his death, ho appears by some means to have diminished. That his losses must have occurred after this Epistle was written, we may ffrhaps infer from v. 7. He lived chiefly on his estate, in the quiet pursuits orace here supposes him to bc engaged in; though immediately after the battle of Actium he accompauicd Messalla into Gaul, and was absent about a year, which, as far as we know, comprised all his active life. Horace, among other blessingS, assigns him good health; nevcrthelcss he died young. It appears that, while many disparaged Horace's writings, Tibullus judgcd them kindly‚ and the affection the two poets bore onc another cannot bc mis· taken.
